Customer Marketing Data Analysys

Dataset Description

Dataset has been collected from kaggle . This data set was provided to students for their final project in order to test their statistical analysis skills as part of a MSc. in Business Analytics. It can be utilized for EDA, Statistical Analysis, and Visualizations. For more specific guidance on how to utilize this data set, please see the Exploratory & Statistical Analysis task.

The is a CSV file of 2240 observations (customers) with 28 variables related to marketing data. More specifically, the variables provide insights about:

  • Customer profiles
  • Products purchased
  • Campaign success (or failure)
  • Channel performance

We are not sure the year data is coming from. Althrough we can assume it's coming from 2014, because this is the last recent year in column "Dt_Customer".

Columns:

  • ID: Customer's Unique Identifier
  • Year_Birth: Customer's Birth Year
  • Education: Customer's education level
  • Marital_Status: Customer's marital status
  • Income: Customer's yearly household income
  • Kidhome: Number of children in customer's household
  • Teenhome: Number of teenagers in customer's household
  • Dt_Customer: Date of customer's enrollment with the company
  • Recency: Number of days since customer's last purchase
  • MntWines: Number of purchases containing wine in the last 2 years
  • MntFruits: Number of purchases containing fruits in the last 2 years
  • MntMeatProducts: Number of purchases containing meat in the last 2 years
  • MntFishProducts: Number of purchases containing fish in the last 2 years
  • MntSweetProducts: Number of purchases containing sweets in the last 2 years
  • MntGoldProds: Number of purchases containing gold in the last 2 years
  • NumDealsPurchases: Number of purchases made with a discount
  • NumWebPurchases: Number of purchases made through the company's web site
  • NumCatalogPurchases: Number of purchases made using a catalogue
  • NumStorePurchases: Number of purchases made directly in stores
  • NumWebVisitsMonth: Number of visits to company's web site in the last month
  • AcceptedCmp1: 1 if customer accepted the offer in the 1st campaign, 0 otherwise (Target variable)
  • AcceptedCmp2: 1 if customer accepted the offer in the 2nd campaign, 0 otherwise (Target variable)
  • AcceptedCmp3: 1 if customer accepted the offer in the 3rd campaign, 0 otherwise (Target variable)
  • AcceptedCmp4: 1 if customer accepted the offer in the 4th campaign, 0 otherwise (Target variable)
  • AcceptedCmp5: 1 if customer accepted the offer in the 5th campaign, 0 otherwise (Target variable)
  • Response: 1 if customer accepted the offer in the last campaign, 0 otherwise (Target variable)
  • Complain: 1 if customer complained in the last 2 years, 0 otherwise
  • Country: Customer's location

Customer Profile

Age and Education

Looking at the distribution of clients on the graph 1.1. we see that most of customers is in their 40s. The average age is 45.08, what seems to be a high score. Median for customer age is 44, when mode for this variable is positioned on 38. What may be suprising is fact in dataset we've found some people around 120s, what suggests that dataset is really old or data is not clean - those records were treated as non-reliable outliers and removed from the scratch. Looking at mode and median shows there may be some outliers making average and median higher than it suppose to be. After rejecting 10% the highest and the smallest age values, the trimmed mean has been calculated with 45.02 as an outcome. The reasult is not really as I've expected. The trimmed median is acctually higher than the median calculated from whole dataset.

Additionaly we can draw a conclusion that current marketing style attracts customers with a graduation diploma. There's only small amount of buyers with basic education level.

To get a better understanding of people age and their education coming from the dataset it's worth to look at this from different point. On the picture 1.3 we can see a big advantage of educated customers. No other essential conclusions from image 1.3.

Family

Next interesting aspect is if current marketing brings customers with childrens.

A bold statement can be made - there's no clear connection between customers children age classification - some of customers have childrens, others have teenagers. What can be said instead - the company attracts people with kids. Most of customers have at least one child.

Marital status

Another interesting aspect of customers lifestyle is their marital status.

Customers are mostly living in some kind of relationship (64,6%) - partly legalised (married), partly not (together).

Income

The mean yearly household income of analysed group is $52236.58. We can observe an occuring outlier which is highly increasing the average yearly income. The amount of this household is $666666.00. The minimum household income amoung customers is $1730.00. The average household income has been marked on picture with yellow line, and the median with pointed black line.

We see on the picture 4.1 small amount of people beeing outliers in yearly income aspect. To get a better and closer view outlier values have been removed from the graph 4.2. As we can see - it doesn't have a big influence to median or mean income.

Relation between the household income ond total orders has been showed excluding income outliers to get a better scope of view.

Campaign and company analyze

Leading company products

What the graph is suggesting - future selling should be focused on wines. Other products are just a fillers when you compare quantities. Another strategy may be increasing customers attention to other products by giving better opportunities while buying wines. Wines must be the most profitable so it's worth to care about this customer segment and try to become a top position in customer thoughts associated with wine products.

New Customers

Sadly we don't know when campaigns took a place in time so we can't point if increases of new customers on August 2012, October 2013, March 2014 and May 2014 were related to them.

Store or online? - shopping style

What may be suprising in time of the Internet - company benefits the most on directly sale in shops (at least if we look at the quantity of purchases by type). Another suprising fact is that catalogue sale is still high. It may be connected with the average age group of customers or types of offered products. What can be seen - catalogs are worth to keep. Next question is if the company website is comfortable and easy to-use for potential clients? Considering categories of products from the shop offer another possibility is that people likes to see and experience food products to make sure those are fresh as it is expected.

Almost 1/5 of total orders are deal purchases. Regular offer is responsible only for 81.5% purchases.

What may be suprising considering that most of purchases had a place in a store, most tracked customers visited a store website at least once during the last tracking month. The average of visits per person is 5. The fact, that older customers are keep visiting the website is satisfying.

The overal outcome is not looking bad. The highest score in days since last customer purchase is 99. What is satisfying - olders customers haven't higher scores since last purchases than newers, what means that most of customers stays with the company in a longer relation. The average score for days since last buy is placed on 49.0 days.

Customer satisfaction

Complain rate is low. The company should at least try to handle this score or try to go closer to the 0.

Advertising campaign outcomes

Whatever company did in recent advertasing campain - it should keep it going. This is the only one when sale during campaing had such a big increase. Comparing with other campaings - the average increase was 200%. On the other hand, 2nd campaign may be consideres as a failure. Where was it reaching (to which customers group) and was was offered during this time - those are aspects we should get a closer look into. For now we don't have enough information to evaluate this.

Global company reach

The range of company reach is global. However, the vast majority of orders had a place in Spain.

The advertising company reach has been showed on the picture 10.2. The good thing is that campaigns reach countries beasides Spain.

Most of complains have a source in Spain, which is good considering that sell in Spain is the highest and there's no neglecting in other countries, but it's not good there were any at all. Few complains were noted in South Africa (3) and in Canada (2). Single complain occured in Germany.
